post_text:
Statement from the Brookline School Committee: https://buff.ly/3havZt5

"The School Committee appreciates the intense public interest in our ongoing negotiations with the Brookline Educators Union over an agreement for the 2020-2021 school year. Our discussions with the union have been amicable, and both sides have shown flexibility. Last week, we reached an agreement on expectations for the ten work days before students start returning to our buildings on September 16. This week, we will continue working with the union to arrive at a formal agreement that will govern in-person and remote instruction during the rest of the school year. '

We are grateful for the heroic efforts of our educators, administrators, and district staff, who are working at full stretch to develop schedules, design curricula, and prepare our classrooms to welcome back all of our students as soon as possible."

School Committee Negotiations Subcommittee:
Suzanne Federspiel and Andy Liu

During the temporary closure of the Public Schools of Brookline, students who qualify for free or reduced-price meals will be offered meals at no cost through the district's online student ordering system.

Families can access grab-and-go prepared meals at one of four locations (Coolidge Corner School, Pierce School, Brookline High School, and Baker School) every Monday, Wednesday, and Friday from 12:00 to 1:30 p.m. This service will begin on TODAY on March 17. Families can also place an order and request a curbside pick-up time on the PSB Food Service website: https://buff.ly/34HN08T

URGENT: In following the guidelines set forth by the CDC, Massachusetts Department of Health, and the Brookline Department of Public Health, Brookline Public Schools will be closed through Tuesday, April 7 for the health and well-being of our community.

We are also strongly encouraging “social distancing” (staying out of large groups and maintaining 6-feet of separation at smaller gatherings) to lower the risk of transmission of illness to others. We urge families to discontinue play dates and social gatherings entirely to limit any potential for community spread. (Updated: 3/16/20) Learn more: https://buff.ly/2TXdr7j

Following the Town of Brookline’s announcement of the cancellation of all non-essential public meetings, the Public Schools of Brookline will also cancel all non-essential evening meetings, gatherings, and community events in our school buildings effective immediately and through April 30, 2020.
